Assignment 1

Review the scenario.

Our team needs to explore GP appointment records. The NHS must balance its infrastructure and staffing capacity against patient demand, understand missed appointment trends, and gauge whether external signals like Twitter/X can provide additional insight. Stakeholders are divided, some call for expanded capacity, others for better utilisation of existing resources.

Summarise the business questions.

  1. Has there been adequate staff and capacity in the GP networks to meet appointment demand?
  2. What is the actual utilisation of GP resources like appointment durations and wait times?
  3. How have missed appointments varied over time, region and appointment mode, and how did data capture issues like JuneNovember2018 affect these rates?
  4. Can sentiment from Twitter/X help explain patterns in attendance or capacity strain?

Plan your initial analytic approach.

Capacity vs. Demand: Well use the appointments_regional.csv to count how many appointment slots were offered by region, month, and mode and compare that to how many were actually booked and attended. Well also use the monthly coverage data which is the number of practices included vs. total practices to adjust for missing reporting. By calculating the ratio of booked slots to available slots over time and by region, we can spot where and when capacity falls short.

Resource Utilisation: From actual_duration.csv, well clean the actual_duration values and from appointments_regional.csv well get wait times which is the days between the booking and appointment. Well then find summary statistics like the average, median, and distribution and create boxplots to see how long appointments take and how long patients wait, broken down by appointment mode and region.

Missed Appointments (DNA): Using appointments_regional.csv, well filter the appointment_status column to get counts of Did Not Attend (DNA) and Attended. Well calculate the DNA rate as DNA (Attended + DNA) for each region and month. Well plot this over time, paying special attention to the JuneNovember2018 period when DNA counts were under reported.

External Signals (Twitter/X): Well load tweets.csv and extract relevant hashtags and keywords. Then well count tweets and run a simple sentiment score per week or month. By overlaying these social media trends on our DNA and capacity plots, we can see if spikes in frustration or discussions like #GP, #healthcare align with appointment outcomes.

1. actual_duration.csv

Data quality & stats:

The actual_duration column is stored as text, so we must convert it into numbers.

Once numeric, youll see most appointments last 812minutes, with a long tail stretching up to 60minutes.

Any durations <1minute or >60minutes are grouped into an Unknown / Data Quality Issue categorytheyre almost certainly recording errors.

Other columns to watch:

appointment_date: lets you plot daily trends.

appointment_mode (facetoface, telephone, online): to compare how long each type takes.

sub_icb_location_code / sub_icb_location_name: for regional breakdowns.

2. appointments_regional.csv

Data quality & stats:

The appointment_status field covers: Attended, DNA, Unknown. Due to complications between statuses Available, Booked, Cancelled, About 36% become Unknown each month.

From JuneNovember2018, DNAs are underreported for practices using TPP SystmOneso youll see an artificial dip in Did Not Attend counts over that period.

After July2019, a growing share of appointment_mode shows up as Unknown (because some systems cant supply mode data).

Other columns to watch:

appointment_month: perfect for clean monthbymonth trends.

hcp_type: splits GPs from other practice staff (though only GP is reliably captured).

time_between_book_and_appointment: how many days patients waitkey for understanding DNAs and capacity strain.

3. national_categories.xlsx

Data quality & stats:

context_type (CareRelated Encounter, Inconsistent Mapping, Unmapped) and national_category show that 1015% of slots end up Unmapped or Inconsistent, meaning practices havent mapped local appointment types cleanly.

service_setting (General Practice, PCN, Extended Access, Other, Unmapped) also has a notable Unmapped bucket where external providers or shared slots arent clearly recorded.

Other columns to watch:

service_setting: to compare noshow rates or durations between GP vs. PCN vs. Extended Access slots.

national_category: to drill into specific clinic types (e.g. Structured Medication Review vs. General Consultation Routine).

ONS codes (icb_ons_code, region_ons_code): handy for merging in population or socioeconomic data.

Tip for all three files:

The count_of_appointments column appears everywhereuse it to weight your analyses (e.g., DNArate = DNA/(count_of_appointments for Attended + DNA)). And dont forget to filter or flag all those Unknown values before drawing conclusions.

Summarise and explain any trends you've identified for both aggregated monthly and seasonal visualisations.

Range & Peaks/Troughs: Total appointments by month (across all service settings) vary from roughly 23.8 million (Aug 2021) up to 30.4 million (Nov 2021). The top three months are November 2021 (30.4 M), October 2021 (30.3 M), and March 2022 (29.6 M). The lowest points occur in August 2021 (23.85 M) and April 2022 (23.91 M). Underlying Drivers The OctoberNovember 2021 surge likely reflects ramped-up routine care after the summer lull and the end of the school holidays. The March 2022 peak comes just before Easterclinics push to clear backlogs before the holiday. Summer slowdown (July/August) and Easter trough (April) are the two clearest dip periods.

Seasonal Breakdowns (Here each season groups its constituent months to highlight quarter-to-quarter shifts.) Season Months Trend Summer 2021 JunAug 21 (Aug only) Lowest volumes, reflecting holiday slowdown. Autumn 2021 SepNov 21 Steady rise: ~25.9 M ~27.4 M ~27.8 M as clinics reopen after summer. Winter 202122 Dec 21Feb 22 Plateau around 2323.5 M, with a slight Jan bump (New Year catch-up). Spring 2022 MarMay 22 V-shape: high in March (~26.1 M), dip in April (~21.0 M) over Easter, then recovery in May (~24.0 M).

Common Patterns Across Service Settings & Categories General Practice dominates every season by an order of magnitude over other settings, but it still mirrors the same seasonal rhythm. Primary Care Network, Unmapped, Other, etc., all display Autumn ramp, Winter plateau, Spring V-shape, and Summer trough in lockstep with the aggregate. Among national categories, General Consultation (Acute & Routine) drive most appointments; they too surge in Autumn, dip in Summer, and show the Eastertime lull in April.

Implications Staffing & Resources should flex up in OctoberNovember and again in March, then plan for lower capacity in summer months and Easter. Backlog management: anticipate spikes just before holiday dips and schedule catch-up slots post-holiday (May/January). Predictable seasonality can inform appointment-booking windows, supply ordering, and patient-communication campaigns to smooth demand.

            cleaned = re.match(r'#\w+', token.lower())
            if cleaned:
                tags.append(cleaned.group())

Do you think it is useful to look at these columns in more detail?

The tweet_retweet_count and tweet_favorite_count columns measure engagementhow widely a tweet was amplified or liked. Their value counts and summary statistics reveal a highly skewed distribution: most tweets have low or zero engagement, while a small number have very high counts. Visualising on a log scale helps expose the long tail without those few popular tweets dominating the view.

It is useful to inspect these columns further because:

High-engagement tweets (high retweets/favorites) likely carry outsized influence and could be weighted more heavily when surfacing trending topics or validating sentiment.

Outliers (very large counts) may point to viral content or key influencers.

However, relying solely on high-engagement tweets risks missing emerging themes present in lower-visibility tweets, so a balanced approach (e.g., all hashtags but annotated or weighted by engagement) is preferable.

1. How your team can use tweets to provide feedback to stakeholders

Show what people are talking about in real time. Collect and summarise the top hashtags and recurring keywords so stakeholders see current public concerns (e.g., about booking, waiting times, missed appointments). Measure sentiment and engagement. Use likes and retweets to surface which topics resonate most high engagement tweets signal issues or messages that need attention. Track trends and spikes. Visualise increases in certain themes like sudden rise in complaints about capacity so stakeholders can act quickly. Provide voice of the public examples. Include anonymysed representative sample tweets to give colour and context behind the numbers, this turns abstract metrics into relatable feedback. Close the loop with communication. Use Twitter not just to listen but to respond or clarify on things like public updates, and then report back to stakeholders on how messaging changed perception.

2. Do the tweets add value to the overall project?

Yes. Tweets add external, real-time context that internal data alone may miss. They surface unsolicited patient sentiment, complaints, praise, or confusion, helping validate or explain patterns seen in appointment data. They act as an early warning system for emerging problems like sudden negative chatter about access issues, so the NHS can investigate before issues escalate. They help prioritise actions by showing which topics have the most public attention via hashtag frequency and engagement. I believe the value is greatest when tweets are treated as a complementary signal, not the sole source because social media can be noisy and skewed.

3. How the NHS can utilise tweets

Monitor public sentiment around service availability, capacity, and patient experience to inform operational decisions. Run and coordinate campaigns using official hashtags to encourage behaviours like reminders, vaccination drives, appointment booking guides. Respond to misinformation or confusion quickly by seeing what questions or myths are circulating and correcting them publicly. Amplify positive stories or successful initiatives to build trust and awareness. Engage directly with users for basic service support or guidance and then feed those interaction insights back to planners.

4. Suggestions to improve future data collection or analysis

Define clear goals and key topics to track like missed appointments or wait times so the hashtag keyword extraction is focused. Capture engagement metrics like likes and retweets alongside raw tweet text to help weight importance. Aggregate and visualise trends over time to distinguish noise from sustained issues. For example compare daily and weekly volume of a hashtag. Use consistent, official hashtags in NHS messaging to make tracking easier and reduce fragmentation. Combine listening with response. track the impact of public replies or campaigns to close the feedback loop.

Question 1 Should the NHS start looking at increasing staff levels?

Overall capacity is generally sufficient: Most months daily demand sits below the 1,200,000-appointments-per-day guidelineutilisation hovers in the 7090 % range.

Peak months push capacity: In November 2021 (the busiest month) and again in early 2022, utilisation climbs to around 95100 % of that planning figure. Those near-capacity peaks coincide with known seasonal pressures (e.g. winter respiratory illness).

Actionable insight: While routine staffing levels appear adequate for the average month, the NHS should consider flexible staffing models (e.g. temporary staff, extended hours, surge teams) to handle those periodic spikes without overworking core staff or compromising patient care.

Recommendation: Rather than a blanket increase in headcounts year-round, focus on bolstering capacity ahead of and during high-demand periods (especially November and the winter months) to keep utilisation below critical levels. Implement rolling forecasts and just-in-time staffing adjustments guided by these utilisation trends.

Question 2 How do the healthcare professional types differ over time?

GPs deliver the lions share of appointments. At every point, GPled visits (blue line) are 1525 % higher than those by other practice staff (orange line).

Both GP and otherstaff volumes follow the same seasonal pattern. Both peak in OctoberNovember 2021 and again around March 2022, then dip over the DecemberJanuary winter lull and spring.

Other Practice Staff play a significant but secondary role. Their total volumes mirror GPs rises and falls, suggesting theyre being used in parallel (e.g., triage, minor clinics) when demand surges.

Unknown appointments are negligible. The tiny green line shows truly missing HCP information is under 1 % and doesnt materially affect capacity planning.

Implication: The NHS workforce is heavily GP-centric, but other staff capacity flexes in tandem. If the goal is to better smooth demand peaks, it may be more efficient to expand the use of non-GP clinicians (nurses, pharmacists, etc.) during those high-demand months rather than hiring more GPs.

Question 3 Are there significant changes in whether or not visits are attended?

Attended appointments (blue) dominate by a huge margin and follow the same seasonal peaks and dips as overall volume.

DNA (Did Not Attend) and Unknown (orange & green) both stay very low (around 5 %6 % of total) and track each other closely.

Proportions remain stable: the ratio of DNAs and Unknown to attended barely shifts month-to-month, even during peak demand.

Conclusion: Attendance rates are consistently high, with only a small, stable share of no-shows and unknowns. Theres no large swing in patient non-attendance over the periodso the NHSs challenges around missed appointments appear to be a persistent, low-level issue rather than one that spikes dramatically in certain months.

Question 4 Are there changes in terms of appointment type and the busiest months?

Face-to-face dominates: It consistently accounts for the largest share of appointmentspeaking around 1920 million in OctNov 2021 and Mar 2022, and dipping to about 15 million in December 2021 and April 2022.

Telephone is the main remote channel: It runs second, between 810 million monthly, mirroring the same peaks and troughs as in-person visits.

Home visits, Video/Online, and Unknown remain very low:

Home visits hover around 100200 thousand per month.

Video/Online appointments are under 200 thousand, showing limited adoption.

Unknown modes are similarly negligible.

Conclusion: Even during the busiest months, the NHS relies overwhelmingly on face-to-face and telephone appointments. Video/online and home visits play only a small supporting role. To alleviate pressure on in-person services, the NHS could consider expanding and promoting remote modalitiesespecially video/onlinesince telephone capacity already scales but video remains under-utilised.

Question 5 Are there any trends in time between booking and appointment?

Same Day bookings are the largest grouparound 1113 million per monthpeaking in November 2021 and March 2022, and dipping in December and April.

Short-range bookings (27 days) are the next biggest cohort, ranging 47 million, following the same seasonal high/low pattern.

Medium-range windows (814 days; 1 day; 1521 days) trail in that order, each with consistent relative sizes month-to-month.

Long-range bookings (22+ days) and Unknown/Data Quality are very small and stable.

Conclusion: Patients overwhelmingly book for the same day or within one week of their appointment, with those two groups comprising the bulk of demand. The stability of each booking-window segment across the year suggests established patient behaviour patterns.

Implication: To improve access and responsiveness, the NHS could:

Ensure adequate same-day and short-notice capacity (e.g., reserve slots for urgent same-day care).

Monitor the relatively smaller longer-lead bookingsif they grow over time, it may signal a shift in patient planning habits or indicate unmet demand for routine/preventive care.

Overall, the booking-to-appointment intervals are stable, so operational focus should remain on managing high short-notice demand while maintaining capacity for planned appointments.

GP visits dwarf everything else

The General Practice box sits around 2327 million monthly with very little month-to-month spread.

All other settings (Extended Access, Other, PCN, Unmapped) are an order of magnitude lowermostly under 1 million per month.

Among non-GP services, Unmapped shows the greatest variability

When GP is excluded, Unmapped ranges roughly 0.81.4 million, suggesting inconsistent categorisation or changing volume in external/third-party provision.

Primary Care Network sits around 0.50.7 million; Other around 0.450.55 million; and Extended Access Provision around 0.180.22 million.

Conclusion:

The bulk of workload is handled by core GP practices.

Of the ancillary settings, Primary Care Networks and Other services have steady, moderate volume, while Unmapped appointments fluctuate significantlythis points to data-quality or classification issues that should be resolved to accurately plan resources.

Recommendation: Focus on cleaning and mapping the Unmapped category, and consider whether expanding capacity in Primary Care Networks could help smooth demand on GP services.

Overall Insights & Trends Across All Analyses

Capacity Utilisation Is High but Predictable

Average daily demand runs at 7090 % of the 1.2 M-appointments/day planning target.

Predictable peaks in Nov 2021 and Mar 2022 push utilisation to 95100 %, while winter holidays and April dips relieve pressure.

Action: Implement flexible, surge staffing (e.g. extra clinics, extended hours) around those known high-demand windows.

Workload Concentrated in Core GP Services

General Practice handles ~90 % of all appointments by volume.

Other Practice Staff, PCNs, and Extended Access fill supportive roles but at far lower volumes (sub-million monthly).

Action: Shift more routine or triage work to non-GP clinicians and strengthen PCN capacity to smooth GP demand.

Appointment Attendance Is Stable & Strong

9497 % of booked appointments are attended each month; DNA (Did Not Attend) and Unknown together hold steady at 36 %.

No dramatic spikes in no-shows during peaksmissed-appointment interventions (e.g. reminders) should target the persistent baseline.

Action: Pilot targeted reminder campaigns for the ~3 % noshow group to reclaim capacity and improve equity.

Face-to-Face & Telephone Dominate, Video Under-utilised

In-person (~1520 M/mo) and telephone (~810 M/mo) appointments mirror overall surges.

Video/online sessions remain below 200 K/mo, indicating untapped digital capacity.

Action: Expand and promote video-consultation workflows to relieve in-person load, especially during seasonal peaks.

Patients Book Largely on the Same Day or Within a Week

Same-day bookings are the largest cohort (~1113 M/mo), followed by 27 days out (~57 M/mo).

These patterns hold steady across months, signaling stable patient behaviour.

Action: Reserve slots for high same-day demand and monitor longer-lead bookings to spot emerging shifts in planning behaviour.

Data-Quality Gaps in Unmapped Service Settings

The Unmapped category (appointments that couldnt be mapped to a known setting) varies widely (0.81.4 M/mo).

Cleaning and consistently mapping these will strengthen planning accuracy.

Action: Review mapping rules with system suppliers and backfill historical unmapped records where possible.

High-frequency hashtags (e.g. #nhs, #covid19) track public chatter; filtering out generic tags surfaces more actionable topics.

Engagement metrics (retweets, likes) highlight which issues resonate most, serving as an early-warning system.
